message.content: This question requires some basic knowledge about electrical conductors and insulators. An electrical insulator is a material that does not allow the flow of electric current. Metal (option A) is incorrect because it is a good conductor of electricity. Cement (option B) is also incorrect because it contains conductive materials and can conduct electricity. Stone (option C) is incorrect because some types of stone, such as quartz, can conduct electricity. Brick (option D) is the correct answer because it is made of non-conductive materials like clay and shale, and therefore acts as an insulator.

This question requires basic knowledge about electrical conduction and insulation. An electrical insulator is a material that does not conduct electricity and inhibits the flow of electrical current. Options (A), (B), and (C) are all conductors of electricity, meaning they allow the flow of electrical current. Option (D), brick, is a poor conductor of electricity and is commonly used as an insulating material in electrical systems.

Brick, option (D), is a good example of an electrical insulator as it does not conduct electricity easily. It is commonly used as an insulating material in construction and electrical installations.
